        <p data-uuid="696e73ade6c4483199da8b4ac40d24b5">Writer Helen Hunt Jackson published a book that pushed for reform of U.S. Indian policy in 1881. Titled <i>A Century of Dishonor</i>, it described the mistreatment of many Native American groups in an attempt to force the government to establish fairer policies.</p>
        <section class="historical-source nobg" data-uuid="c4a7b12da0d74e47920a04ed59dc14c7">
            <article class="box gradient" data-uuid="650aafeff80b45b7bd06880831f904ee">
                <div class="header-element" data-uuid="a6ddea5282e541099f05b1119cdd0b8f">
                    <h2 class="label" data-uuid="b5f2a3fea2ce423391bb6585ad291272">Historical Source</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="jonra" data-uuid="98858ec6be11458d8f2bf8c9a48b9165">
                    <h2 data-uuid="1902e2c1876f4ea79c5ba65100d48701"></h2>
                    <h2 data-uuid="dd4c9663bc76417788f8d9c0e2bc99e1"><i>A Century of Dishonor</i></h2>
                    <p class="source" data-uuid="558e060fa30b4ba99a0c07b206475855">Helen Hunt Jackson wrote <i>A Century of Dishonor</i> because she was shocked to learn about the long history of mistreatment of Native Americans in the United States. She hoped her book would make more Americans aware of their situation and would force that government to act. In the book’s Introduction, Jackson blames the U.S. government for not dealing fairly and consistently with Native Americans.</p>
                </div>
