                            upon their means of <b><a href="[remark:4819b595798f431288f30e8782c82dec]">subsistence</a></b> without furnishing them any proper
                            return; we have shut them up on reservations often <b><a href="[remark:f690f3b66e15429c8188731df99f45a5]">notoriously</a></b> unfit for
                            them, or, if fit, we have not hesitated to drive them off for our profit,
                            without regard to theirs; we have treated them sometimes as foreign nations,
                            with whom we have had treaties; sometimes as <b><a href="[remark:c36065388c8941168ba960b08560e4c3]">wards</a></b>, who are entitled to
                            no voice in the management of their affairs; and sometimes as subjects, from
                            whom we have required obedience, but to whom we have recognized no
                            obligations.”</p>
                        <div class="pullquote_attribution_wrapper" data-uuid="ca2b4af677824ae59bea77d62cb55e94">
                            <p class="pullquote_address" data-uuid="c2894d56577f41919b8a1b78cf25f21b">—Helen Hunt Jackson,</p>
